snippet.textDisplay: The pilot was on a "Special Visual Flight Requirement" flight plan.  Special VFR, or SVFR, therefore exists as a tool for pilots to continue operating under Visual Flight Rules (VFR) in Instrument Meteorological Conditions (IMC) Said another way, VFR requirements will match those of Class G basic VFR minimums if you are within 1200' of the ground , only requiring 1 mile visibility and clear of clouds

The air traffic safety board lady said the descent took 1 minute. I forget how many feet she said they fell per second. I’m confused. Did they clip the side of a hill with the propeller THEN tumble to the ground and explode? Or did he literally fly them into the ground due to being disoriented like the pilots who flew into the bay at Navarre Beach, FL during heavy fog at night? Either way, it’s all so sad :(
So many young families just devastated:
A father who lost his wife and the mother of his 3 young children. 3 young children who lost their mother.

A mother who lost her daughter. A wife who lost her husband, the father of her 4 children. 3 children who lost their sister and their father.

A brother and sister who lost their sister. A brother and sister who lost their mother and father.

And there’s another mother daughter duo who died. I think that mother leaves behind 2 sons. Those boys lost their sister and their mother. I don’t know anything about the husband of this woman, but if she was married, he lost his wife.

And then there’s the team. They lost 3 teammates and their coach if I’m understanding the relationship of the woman who left behind 3 young children and her husband. I believe she was the coach of the girls’ team.

Just SO much loss. It’s so tragic.
